    {
      "id": "855bd0385d2737a278014318aa59c159d1b4362c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 141,
        "name": "Li Wei",
        "email": "wei.g.li@intel.com",
        "username": "liwei",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-05-30 03:15:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nAndreas, just as a suggestion, I think it would be good if people make comments like the following when uploading patches.  For example, one's patch set 1 got a \"-1\".  Instead of addressing review comments and rebasing to a new parent in _one_ new patch set, she could do _two_ pushes and say:\n\n  - Patch set 2 addresses review comments---no rebases.\n  - Patch set 3 is purely a rebase---no fixes.\n\nSo that the reviewer, which has a high probability to be you ;-), could set \"Old Version History\" to \"patch set 1\" and review patch set 2.  Also pure rebases could be identified and ack'ed much easier.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "5224ec15bf89500460b46d1ef8750d05605f5376",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-05-30 05:22:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nLi Wei, I agree that this would be nice, but it would also be more work for both the developer and the test system.\n\nFor addressing review comments, I think it makes sense to use the \"Reply Done\" comment, though I admit that I don't use this myself consistently.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "18f448d80aae0fbc8bce1e48ceffbc6fbc06bbb0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 141,
        "name": "Li Wei",
        "email": "wei.g.li@intel.com",
        "username": "liwei",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-05-30 05:58:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nThe extra build resulted from \"two pushes\" instead of one could be canceled on Jenkins.  (I routinely do that when refreshing a series of patches.)  But you are right that developers would need to do more.  Hopefully someday Gerrit would be able to subtract the \"rebase\" changes from two patch sets.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
